# Windows & Active Directory Fundamentals + Command Line

## 📖 Overview

This repository contains my notes and hands-on exercises from the **Windows & Active Directory Fundamentals** and **Command Line** modules on TryHackMe.

These modules provide the foundation for Windows administration, Active Directory environments, and Windows command-line usage—essential skills for SOC Analysts, Penetration Testers, and Blue Team professionals.

---

## 🎯 Learning Objectives

- Understand the Windows operating system.
- Learn Active Directory architecture and components.
- Understand domains, domain controllers, users, groups, and OUs.
- Learn how authentication works in Windows.
- Navigate Windows using the Command Prompt.
- Perform file, process, user, and network management using command-line tools.

---

## 📚 Topics Covered

### Windows Fundamentals
- Windows Architecture
- File System
- User Accounts
- NTFS Permissions
- Registry
- Services
- Task Manager
- Event Viewer
- Computer Management
- System Information

### Active Directory Fundamentals
- Domains
- Domain Controllers
- Organizational Units (OUs)
- Users & Groups
- Group Policy (GPO)
- Kerberos
- LDAP
- DNS
- Authentication
- Forests & Trees

### Command Line
- Directory Navigation
- File & Folder Management
- User Management
- Process Management
- Networking Commands
- System Information
- File Permissions
- Environment Variables

---

## 💻 Commands Learned

### Navigation

```cmd
cd
dir
mkdir
rmdir
tree
```

### File Management

```cmd
copy
move
ren
del
type
echo
```

### Networking

```cmd
ipconfig
ipconfig /all
ping
tracert
nslookup
netstat
arp
route
```

### System Information

```cmd
hostname
whoami
systeminfo
tasklist
taskkill
driverquery
```

### User Management

```cmd
net user
net localgroup
```

### Permissions

```cmd
attrib
icacls
```

---

## 🔑 Key Takeaways

- Active Directory centralizes the management of users and computers.
- Domain Controllers authenticate users and enforce security policies.
- Group Policies help secure and manage Windows environments.
- Command Prompt provides powerful administration capabilities.
- Networking commands are essential for troubleshooting and security analysis.

